00:42.540 --> 00:49.700
is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. With this show we're beginning a look at the
fascinating writing career of science fiction author Charles Harness. Born and

00:49.700 --> 00:58.520
raised in Texas, Harness completed his university in law studies in Washington DC.
From 1946 to 1953, Harness produced 13 short stories and two novels. One of the

00:58.520 --> 01:06.600
novels, The Rose, is a classic. Harness completed law school in 1946 so in those
years he was striving to establish a career as a patent lawyer and to support

01:06.600 --> 01:16.340
his family right and it was the financial strain confronting his young family
that encouraged Harness to write science fiction. I was working in Washington as

01:16.340 --> 01:35.020
a mineral economist during the war and going to law school and my daughter was
born in 1946 and there were some bills to be paid and we needed the money so i

01:35.020 --> 01:52.880
sat down and wrote my first science fiction story which was "Time Trap". And this
was bought by what was then Astounding and I thought well gee do they pay money

01:52.880 --> 02:02.680
for this stuff so I thought perhaps I should turn out some more of it which I
did. So Harness cut the writing bug and was able to work full-time and to write

02:02.680 --> 02:12.700
for a few years but he did stop writing in 1953 and he wasn't heard from again
until 1966. Here's what he told us when we asked him about that long gap. I wrote

02:12.700 --> 02:26.620
for a while until my daughter got old enough to demand more and more of my time
so the writing had to come to an end and it didn't really resume again until she

02:26.620 --> 02:38.440
was ready to go off to college. This was in 1964 and I picked it up again. Two of
these early stories Harness published under the pseudonym Leonard Lockhart. The

02:38.440 --> 02:46.200
second of the two, The Professional Look, was a joint effort between Harness and
Theodore Thomas, another patent lawyer. Here, Harness describes the genesis of

02:46.200 --> 02:56.260
these stories and their eventual course. Ted and I we were in the patent
department at sign amid together. I wrote the first Leonard Lockhart story,

02:56.260 --> 03:09.560
"Improbable Profession," and at that time he was writing science articles for the
Stanford Advocate as well as being on the patent in the patent department at

03:09.560 --> 03:22.720
sign amid. So I said to him why don't you and I start this series of stories
about a patent attorney and his problems. Here's the first one. So he said yeah we

03:22.720 --> 03:35.060
can do that, so I wrote the first one. He wrote the second one. No, together we
wrote the second one; it was half and half. And after that I left sign amid and

03:35.060 --> 03:47.380
went to grace and he continued the series, so number three is in all subsequent
stories or his even though the name Leonard Lockhart is still used.

03:54.860 --> 04:04.400
Harness's active writing periods were 1946 to 1953, during which he produced 13
short stories and the two novels, Flight Into Yesteryear also published as A Paradox

04:04.400 --> 04:15.780
Man, and The Rose. 1966 and 1968, with six short stories and the novel The Ring of
Ritornel. And 1974 to the present, which saw publication of Wolfhead, The Catalyst,

04:15.780 --> 04:24.400
Firebird, and The Venetian Court, along with three short stories many of Harness's
works feature mystical elements. Apparently this aspect of life has influenced

04:24.400 --> 04:40.160
Harness a great deal. I did go to a ministerial school at TCU at one time. This is
long long ago and they threw me out for reasons I won't go into here but it was

04:40.160 --> 04:51.140
a wise decision. But I've never lost a mystic plant to lots of things. On our next
show we'll begin to look at Harness's most famous work the rose

