06:21.720 --> 06:29.740
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. 1953 marked the publication of a little
-known science fiction classic, Charles Harness's short novel entitled The Rose.

06:29.980 --> 06:36.480
And we have to say little-known because of the curious history of the book.
Right. First of all, Harness attempted to sell the book in the United States

06:36.480 --> 06:45.380
markets, but the editors were unwilling to buy it. He then had to sell it in
England to a relatively obscure magazine, Authentic Science Fiction. My agent at

06:45.380 --> 06:57.100
the time, Forrest Ackerman of, I think, Los Angeles, peddled it around here and
there. Nobody in this country would buy it. It went to John Campbell, and he wrote

06:57.100 --> 07:08.900
a nice two-line letter bag. He just couldn't use it. It wasn't the kind of thing
that any science fiction magazine or fantasy and science fiction magazine was

07:08.900 --> 07:21.540
publishing at the time. And I should have known better for writing it. But I
wanted to write it, so I did. And finally, Ackerman sold it to this little

07:21.540 --> 07:31.100
Authentic magazine in England, and they published it. Authentic was under the
editorship of H.J. Campbell when The Rose was published. Publication of The Rose

07:31.100 --> 07:38.440
is considered to be the capstone achievement in the generally mediocre 85-issue
run of the magazine. It would have languished in the pages of Authentic were it

07:38.440 --> 07:45.780
not for the fact that the British critics absolutely loved it. Arthur Clarke,
Judith Merril, Brian Aldiss, and in particular Michael Moorcock praised it. It

07:45.780 --> 07:54.140
was through the almost single-handed efforts of Moorcock that The Rose was
published in book form, again in England, some years later. Arthur Clarke saw

07:54.140 --> 08:00.660
it, Dr. Moorcock saw it. And Moorcock was getting into the editor business over
there at that time.

08:04.240 --> 08:17.980
Asked to have his people, Compact Books, publish it. And we have a contract for
that, and they did publish it. Then it was picked up fairly quickly by two other

08:17.980 --> 08:31.680
British outfits in hardcover form. And of course they had to pad it out with the
two other stories to make it in a book size. The two short stories added to pad

08:31.680 --> 08:38.880
the length of the volume in which The Rose was finally published are "The New
Reality" and "The Chess Players." "The New Reality," written in 1950 and first

08:38.880 --> 08:46.140
published in Thrilling Wonder Stories, is considered to be Harness' finest short
story. "The Chess Players" is a clever little story based on the trouble it

08:46.140 --> 08:54.820
develops when a chess club encounters a chess-playing rap. In fact, many of
Harness' works allude to chess. We ask him if he enjoys the game. Well, I loved

08:54.820 --> 09:09.020
to play it, or at least in other years I did. And I still do. I read a book of
chess combinations nearly every night. It puts me to sleep. Various brilliances

09:09.020 --> 09:20.840
of some of the past masters. It's an exciting thing. It wasn't until 1969 that
The Rose was made available in the United States, thanks to the efforts of Damon

09:20.840 --> 09:30.600
Knight. Berkley published it then, and so far that has been the only American
edition. Damon Knight then picked it up from the British. He said, hey, here's

09:30.600 --> 09:41.880
the thing I've been thinking about all these many years, and that's come out in
Britain. Why didn't you give it to me? So, okay. I sold Berkley the rights, the

09:41.880 --> 09:55.220
U.S. rights to it. And that's why all the time lag. If it hadn't been for
Moorcock, it would never have gone anywhere. It struck us that one reason The

09:55.220 --> 10:02.400
Rose could not find a United States publisher in 1953 was that American readers
simply were not ready for a book heavy on the metaphysical rather than the

10:02.400 --> 10:14.100
hardware. We asked Harness if he might agree. You got a point there. They could
live with something like this, whereas over here everybody was guided pretty

10:14.100 --> 10:26.000
much by the dean of science fiction, John Campbell, and he was a hardware man. And
everything had to obey the laws of physics or it would be unacceptable. More

10:26.000 --> 10:27.180
about The Rose on our next show.

