11:57.160 --> 12:04.600
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. On our last show, we talked with science
fiction author Charles Harness about his classic short novel, The Rose. We

12:04.600 --> 12:11.500
learned how The Rose was enthusiastically embraced by the British critics. Yet
it wasn't published in the United States until 16 years had elapsed from its

12:11.500 --> 12:18.500
initial publication in an obscure British magazine. In this show, we'll look at
some of the literary aspects of The Rose. Many of Harness's earlier works were

12:18.500 --> 12:26.380
written hastily, but, we hasten to add, not clumsily. The Rose, on the other
hand, required a considerable length of time for completion. That was one of the

12:26.380 --> 12:38.760
stories where I didn't know how it was going to come out. And in fact, I worked
on that one for two years, Bill. This is not a two-month job. I read all the

12:38.760 --> 12:53.440
books on the arts in the Stanford Public Library. This is one year. I took notes
on them for my entire two weeks' vacation one year. And then it gradually began

12:53.440 --> 13:05.600
to come together. And I used, of course, as you've seen in the story, Oscar
Wilde's story of The Nightingale and the Rose, which I'd read many years

13:05.600 --> 13:14.120
before, and I was quite impressed by it. Harness also filled us in on some other
details about the writing of The Rose. For instance, its early incarnations were

13:14.120 --> 13:27.560
longer, and it originally had another name. Let me give you a little bit more
history on this. There was a time when The Rose was in a longer form, and it had

13:27.560 --> 13:45.340
the name, not The Rose, but Invitation. It was an intergalactic thing, where the
Earth was being examined to see whether it would be admitted into a galactic

13:45.340 --> 14:01.840
brotherhood. And it didn't have the ending that it now has. Damon Knight liked
that, but he couldn't get his publishers to accept it. This, again, was a year

14:01.840 --> 14:15.440
or so before it came out, and it's inauthentic in its short form, which it tells
nothing. So, at that point, I said, maybe I'm going to shorten this thing down,

14:15.560 --> 14:24.920
give it a different ending. So, I did. I cut it from 45,000 words down to, I
think it's about 30,000.

14:30.860 --> 14:39.820
And Ackerman then was able to sell it to the authentic in England. The central
theme of The Rose is difficult to capsule. It's a love story involving two

14:39.820 --> 14:47.760
central characters, Ruy Jacques and Anna van Tuyl. It's set in the midst of a
future confrontation between science and art, and it describes a transcendental

14:47.760 --> 14:54.840
evolution of man into Superman. Harness and his brother Billy, who, as we shall
learn in a later show, died when Harness was still in high school, were the

14:54.840 --> 15:02.560
models for the central characters. Ruy Jacques, again, resembles my brother a
great deal.

15:06.680 --> 15:27.540
And if you can visualize that guy with his sarcasm, his biting wit, his contempt
for all the, well, I don't know. But he was a, he had a high personal integrity

15:27.540 --> 15:48.620
and a impatience with, with, uh, convention and so on. At least in his head, he
did. And I wanted to get him in the print. And, of course, Anna van Tuyl is me,

15:48.840 --> 16:01.560
although I tried to take on a female form to make it effective. I would have, at
one time, I was, I would have been pleased to die if it would bring him back.

16:01.980 --> 16:14.180
But it, of course, that was just being silly. But it was a thought, and it was a
psychic force driving the story. Do yourself a favor. Find a copy of The Rose in

16:14.180 --> 16:15.560
your local used bookstore and read it.

