17:47.840 --> 17:55.840
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. In 1968, Berkley published Charles Harness'
novel, The Ring of Ritornel, his first work to appear in 15 years. It's the

17:55.840 --> 18:03.200
story of two brothers, one a lawyer, the other a poet, and a far distant future.
Here, Harness, who is himself a lawyer, tells us about the very personal

18:03.200 --> 18:15.520
inspiration for the poet. My brother Billy was several years older than I. In
fact, he was nine years older than I. And he died when I was just about to

18:15.520 --> 18:28.940
graduate from high school. He had tumors of the brain, which in those days were
inoperable. Today, it wouldn't be too much trouble to operate if they couldn't

18:28.940 --> 18:45.560
do it then. So, I have remembered him. And I have never let him go. And he has
been in several of my stories. He was the Ring of Ritornel. He was the brother

18:45.560 --> 19:02.920
who was destroyed by the chief bad guy. But his brain was retained. He was the
poet. His name was Omere. In 1977, Wolfhead, Harness's fourth novel, came out. It

19:02.920 --> 19:10.080
was his first novel in nine years. Wolfhead describes a post-atomic holocaust
America and the struggle between various cultures that populate the desolate

19:10.080 --> 19:17.580
land. Harness told us that when he wrote Wolfhead, he went against the
conventional wisdom that one shouldn't write about certain subjects. I started

19:17.580 --> 19:33.220
out writing it. I thought I would do a thing which is frowned upon. You're not
supposed to write post-atomic novels. It's really unacceptable. But here seemed

19:33.220 --> 19:42.440
to be a good one. A real-life character, Richard Nixon, inspired Harness's
characterization of the malevolent leader of the underworld. Well, I thought,

19:42.580 --> 19:54.740
gee, here's this guy. He's about to take over the country. Anything he does is
okay just because he says so. And I'm going to have a character like that in

19:54.740 --> 20:09.940
Wolfhead. So, I put him in there. He was the president of the underworld, and he
would come out and rule the upper world, except he didn't. Even the wolf with

20:09.940 --> 20:24.080
the title was inspired by a real-life dog. The wolf was modeled at the time on
an Alaskan husky dog that lived next door to us. And she and I were great

20:24.080 --> 20:34.040
friends, so I thought I'd put her in it. When Harness reminisced about Wolfhead,
he told us he was pretty much pleased by it. It's one of my happier efforts.

20:35.240 --> 20:36.700
It's not really serious.

20:39.700 --> 20:48.340
Well, some of it is. You know, at one time, it had a different ending. Of
course, we had to ask Harness about that different ending. Keep in mind that

20:48.340 --> 20:54.920
during his writing career, he was a full-time patent attorney. The answer to
this question provides an interesting insight into other ways the real world can

20:54.920 --> 21:00.840
intrude into fiction. And I have to cough when I think about it. Excuse me while
I cough. This is a psycholo...

21:05.760 --> 21:08.080
That was a psychological cough.

21:11.960 --> 21:31.620
In the original ending, the girl lived. But I got involved in some chemical
litigation that I lost. And I was so angry and so disappointed, I said, somebody

21:31.620 --> 21:44.480
has to die. So I killed the heroine and wrote some poetry for her benefit so she
wouldn't feel too badly about it. And that's the poetry, of course, is in the

21:44.480 --> 21:53.400
front and in the back. So that's a little sidelight on that. We'll have more
with Charles Harness on our next show.

