23:25.600 --> 23:32.840
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Science fiction author Charles Harness
began writing in earnest again in the late 70s, and he produced three novels in

23:32.840 --> 23:39.560
short order. The Catalyst is the story of a patent lawyer who works for a
chemical company. In this respect, it resembles some short stories Harness wrote

23:39.560 --> 23:47.720
a decade earlier, "The Alchemist" and "An Ornament to His Profession". The Catalyst
actually started out as a longer, mainstream novel, but Harness, unable to sell

23:47.720 --> 24:01.820
it, fixed it up as a science fiction work. His brother figured heavily in this
book, too. The Catalyst at one time was a general novel, really about my brother

24:01.820 --> 24:13.060
Billy, really about me and my mother, and life in Fort Worth, and life in the
Red Light District, and life in the police department.

24:15.760 --> 24:34.780
And one of the stories there involved a peculiar whistle, which was derived from
Sheep May Safely Graze by Johann Sebastian Bach. But that long version never

24:34.780 --> 24:46.340
sold. And I thought, well, I'm not going to let it die. I will convert it to a
science fiction book. With all the proper trappings and things you need to call

24:46.340 --> 24:57.120
it science fiction, which I did. In 1981, Harness published a novel that was
sort of a throwback to his early period galaxy-galloping days. Firebird is made

24:57.120 --> 25:05.220
up of early Harness devices, such as a time loop and the rebirth of the cosmos.
Here Harness tells us about the basis for the story in Firebird. I'm sure you

25:05.220 --> 25:22.260
recognize the basic story here. This is Tristan and Isolde. I don't know whether
you go in for Wagner or not, but it is Isolde and Tristan drinking what she

25:22.260 --> 25:36.080
thinks is the poison drink, but it's the love of lecture again. And they fall in
love. And after that, just about everything parallels the Tristan and Isolde

25:36.080 --> 25:42.460
story as you would find it in Wagner's opera, including Death at the Inn.

25:46.480 --> 26:00.440
Editor David Hartwell of Pocketbooks also influenced Harness' approach to this
novel. In the beginning, when I first wrote David Hartwell of Pocketbooks, I

26:00.440 --> 26:15.380
should mention, he is a medieval scholar. This is what he got his Ph.D. in
English in. And he was quite familiar with the Tristan legend, a myth. And he

26:15.380 --> 26:29.320
found Welsh origins for it. And he had me change the names to look like Welsh
names. And he said, make him more of a Renaissance knight. So I put in some

26:29.320 --> 26:41.900
chess, which is easy enough. So there was something that looked like a chess
game. I worked it into the plot and it came out okay. Predators are never

26:41.900 --> 26:43.840
content unless they make their contribution.

27:03.560 --> 27:10.560
Harness has retired from his lifelong profession of being a patent attorney.
He's recently produced a couple of short stories in a novel and more are in the

27:10.560 --> 27:19.340
works. He's a gentleman who, while working full-time, produced a small body of
quality science fiction. We asked him how he wishes to be remembered. My request

27:19.340 --> 27:34.500
there is, please forget me. Let me sink into oblivion. Let the waves wash up
over the sand. And everything disappear. Honest to God. We somehow doubt that

27:34.500 --> 27:35.800
Mr. Harness will be forgotten.

